# IGI Diamond Automation — Deployment Notes

## Files in this project
- `app.py` — the Streamlit app
- `packages.txt` — tells Streamlit Cloud to install Chromium + chromedriver at the OS level
- `requirements.txt` — Python dependencies

## Why the old version didn't work on Streamlit Cloud
1. It used `ChromeDriverManager().install()`, which tries to download a
   chromedriver binary from the internet at runtime. Streamlit Cloud's
   network/sandbox blocks or breaks this, so the browser never started.
2. It launched a normal (non-headless) Chrome window. Streamlit Cloud
   servers have no display, so a visible browser cannot open there at all.
3. `packages.txt` was missing entirely, so there was no Chrome/Chromium
   binary on the server in the first place.

## What this version does differently
- Adds `packages.txt` with `chromium` and `chromium-driver`, installed by
  Streamlit Cloud automatically as system packages before your app starts.
- Runs Chrome with `--headless=new`, `--no-sandbox`, and
  `--disable-dev-shm-usage`, which are required for Chrome to run inside
  Streamlit Cloud's containers.
- Looks up the installed Chromium and chromedriver paths directly instead
  of downloading anything at runtime.
- Replaces fixed `time.sleep()` waits with `WebDriverWait`, which moves on
  as soon as the report data actually appears instead of always waiting
  the full fixed number of seconds. This is the main speed gain.
- Reuses a single browser session for the whole batch (`st.cache_resource`)
  instead of implicitly relying on session state alone.
- Adds a "Start Fetching" button so the file is shown for review before
  any browser/scraping work begins.

## Deploying
1. Push these three files to a GitHub repo (root level, not in a subfolder,
   unless you set the app's "Main file path" to match).
2. On https://share.streamlit.io, create a new app pointing at `app.py`.
3. Streamlit Cloud reads `packages.txt` and `requirements.txt`
   automatically — no extra configuration needed.
4. If you edit `packages.txt` after the first deploy, use "Reboot app" in
   the Streamlit Cloud dashboard so the new system packages actually get
   installed.

## About the Cloudflare "Verify you are human" check
A real Cloudflare human-verification challenge cannot be solved by code —
there is no display on the cloud server and no person available to click
it remotely. If this triggers mid-batch, the app will:
- Stop the batch at that certificate
- Keep all rows already fetched
- Show an error telling you to wait a bit and click "Start Fetching" again

This matches running the app fully cloud-hosted: most batches should pass
through, since you mentioned it only appears once per session for you, but
occasional manual restarts may be needed if the server's IP gets flagged.

If this becomes frequent, the more reliable long-term fix is asking IGI
about an official data/API access for verified report lookups, since
scraping around a bot-protection wall isn't something I can help
circumvent.
